\begin{minipage}{0.73\linewidth}
^^IBeing independent is something completely different from being disjoint. Furthermore, for mutually exclusive, disjoint events with positive probabilities,
^^Iif $A$ occurs $\then$ $B$ can't occur, so it gives us a lot of information. Therefore:
^^I\bcentering{\textbf{Disjoint events are not independent}} \vspace{-2mm}
^^I\bcentering{\textbf{Independence is a relation about information}}
^^IIf one of the events is impossible $\then$ They are \textbf{trivially independent}.
